The surface of the ovary close to the organ's midline.
The surface of the ovary further from the organ's midline.
The opening located within the uterus at the uterotubal junction and accessible via hysteroscopy. Occlusion at this opening is referred to as proximal tubal occlusion.
A breast feminized in a transgender woman, typically due to hormones and/or surgery in a transgender woman.
A breast masculinized in a transgender man, typically due to surgery and/or hormones.
A breast virilized in a cisgender man, typically without external hormones and/or surgery.
A breast feminized in a cisgender woman, typically without external hormones and/or surgery.
A human body of a transgender individual.
The body of a cisgender person, typically unmodified by external hormone or surgery administration, although this may not always be the case.
The body of a human who has a female gender identity.
The body of a human who has a male gender identity.
A human body of a cisgender individual who has a male gender identity.
A human body of a cisgender individual who has a female gender identity.
A human body of a transgender individual who has a female gender identity.
A human body of a transgender individual who has a male gender identity.
A state of being related to an organism's health.
A broad term that includes all diseases, lesions, disorders, or nonpathologic condition that normally receives medical treatment, such as pregnancy or childbirth.
Any kind of illness or circumstance which requires medical monitoring.
Any condition that impairs the normal functioning of the body. For this reason, diseases are associated with dysfunctioning of the body's normal homeostatic processes.
The patient's personal experience of their disease.
A functional abnormality or disturbance.
A condition related to one's mental health and/or well-being; or mental state, generally.
Any of various health conditions or states related to pregnancy.
Any of various conditions related to one's sexual health.

Information content entity that is an empirical result found to be meaningful to one or more person(s) or a community, such that it can be interpreted by them in ways that they value, and which arises from a systematic analytic and/or deliberative process of investigation and study of other information content entities, that are often, but not exclusively other data item(s), thereby accounting for those other information content entities.
A knowledge content entity comprised of a data item about some thing.
Objective evidence of disease perceptible to the examining healthcare provider.
Subjective evidence of disease perceived by the patient.
Biological entity which consists of a maximum number of some instances of discontinuous members of the same class.
A set of medical signs and symptoms that are correlated with each other and, often, with a particular disease or disorder.

A syndrome is composed of a set of several clinically recognizable features, signs (observed by someone other than the patient), symptoms (reported by the patient), phenomena or characteristics that often occur together.

A behavioral or mental pattern that causes significant distress or impairment of personal functioning. Such features may be persistent, relapsing and remitting, or occur as a single event. Many disorders have been described, with signs and symptoms that vary widely between specific disorders.

A medical condition that impairs normal functioning of bodily processes that remains largely undetected under examination, dissection or even under a microscope. At the exterior, there is no appearance of abnormality.

A classification ised in educational settings that allows educational institutions to provide special education and related services to students who have displayed poor social and/or academic progress; any of various disorders considered as falling under this classification.
Any of various disorders with primary symptoms affecting emotional state or status.
Any of various diseases affecting the genitourinary system.
Any of various diseases affecting the genital system.
Clinical entity defined by a set of morphological abnormalities resulting from a developmental anomaly involving more than one morphogenetic field. Includes sequences and associations.
A syndrome characterized by the presence of congenital abnormalities that affect more than one organ or system.
A term that refers to the classification of a disorder according to the anatomic site that is involved in the pathologic process.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the genital system.

A stage of human development following early childhood and preceding adolescence. It commonly ends with the beginning of puberty, but may also be defined as ending with the start of the teenage years. For example, the age range is commonly designated as 10–13 years.
The period of development immediately prior to the onset of puberty when changes occur that lead to sexual maturity.
A infectious disease caused by a virus of the family Retroviridae.
